Hormone Replacement Therapy (HRT) is **not** primarily indicated for the **prevention of Coronary Artery Disease (CAD)** due to increased cardiovascular risks (e.g., stroke, venous thromboembolism) in some populations. It remains beneficial for **hot flashes, osteoporosis, and vaginal atrophy** in select patients. Guidelines (e.g., WHI) now emphasize individualized risk-benefit assessment for CAD prevention.
